X.pca.scaled<-prcomp(X, scale=TRUE) # uses correlation matrix

When we do PCA with the correlation matrix, circle plots give us a way of interpretting the principal components:

library(factoextra) 
# you will need to install the factoextra 
# package the first time you use it.

fviz(X.pca.scaled, element='var')

They plot the correlation between the first two transformed scores, \(y_1\) and \(y_2\), and the original variables \(x_i\).

cor(cbind(X.pca.scaled$x[,1:2], X))[3:6, 1:2]
                    PC1         PC2
Sepal.Length  0.8901688 -0.36082989
Sepal.Width  -0.4601427 -0.88271627
Petal.Length  0.9915552 -0.02341519
Petal.Width   0.9649790 -0.06399985

This allows us to see that PC1 is primarily a measure of petal length and width and sepal length, whereas PC2 is a measure of sepal width.

It is plotted on a circle because it is possible to show that \[\sum_{j=1}^p {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(y_j, x_i)^2 = 1\] where \(x_i\) are the original variables, and \(y_j\) the transformed variables. Thus \[\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}(y_1,x_i)^2+\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}(y_2, x_i)^2\leq 1.\]

You can read more about the plotting ability of fviz here. It is possible to do some elegant plots showing the projected data, on top of the circle correlations allowing us to really see the difference between the groups. For example:

fviz_pca_biplot(X.pca.scaled, label = "var", habillage=iris$Species,
               addEllipses=TRUE, ellipse.level=0.95,
               ggtheme = theme_minimal())

What has gone wrong - why don’t they agree? Two things have happened. Firstly there are small numerical errors that occur due to rounding errors. The second is that the eigenvectors are only determined upto multiplication by \(\pm 1\). If we divide them, we can see they are essentially the same:

Petal.Width    1  -1  -1   1

Now we will do the same thing again, but using the svd command.

  • Compute the column centred data matrix \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\mathbf H\mathbf X\).
Solution 
Xtilde = Xcent/sqrt(149)
  • Compute the SVD of \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\mathbf H\mathbf X\) and \(\mathbf H\mathbf X\). How are the two sets of singular values related, and how do they relate to the eigenvalues computed previously. Are the singular vectors of \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\mathbf H\mathbf X\) and \(\mathbf H\mathbf X\) the same?

Q2

In this question we will look at the crabs data from the MASS R package. We will focus on the 5 continuous variables, all measured in mm:

  • FL = frontal lobe size
  • RW = rear width
  • CL = carapace length
  • CW = carapace width
  • BD = body depth.
library(MASS)
?crabs # look at the help page.
X = crabs[,4:8]
  • Carry out PCA on the data in \(X\) using the correlation matrix, including obtaining a scree plot and plotting the PC scores.
Solution 
crabs.pca <- prcomp(X, scale=TRUE) # do PCA
plot(crabs.pca) # scree plot

plot(crabs.pca$x[,1], crabs.pca$x[,2]) # PC2 vs PC1.

By adding colour we can see some patterns. The easiest way is to install the ggfortify package.

library(ggfortify)
autoplot(crabs.pca, data = crabs, colour='sex', scale=FALSE, shape='sex')

This has coloured the points by sex. We can see there is clearly a difference between male and female crabs.

  • Do you have any suggestions for an interpretation for the first two principal components? Circle plots may help.
Solution

The first PC appears to be a measure of overall size:

crabs.pca$rotation[,1]
       FL        RW        CL        CW        BD 
0.4520437 0.4280774 0.4531910 0.4511127 0.4511336

The second PC primarily measures RW. However, as it only represents 3% of the total variation, it is not worth thinking too hard about an interpretation (there is a risk of over-interpretting and reading too much into random noise).

crabs.pca$rotation[,2]
        FL         RW         CL         CW         BD 
 0.1375813 -0.8981307  0.2682381  0.1805959  0.2643219

The circle plot confirms this interpretation:

fviz(crabs.pca, element='var')

Note that there is a clear sex dependence here; female crabs have higher positive PC2 score (corresponding to big FL, RW, BD, and smaller Carapace).

autoplot(crabs.pca, data = crabs, colour='sex')

  • Do you think an analysis based on the sample covariance matrix \({\bf S}\) or the correlation matrix \({\bf R}\) is preferable with this dataset?
Solution

This doesn’t make a big difference as the measurements are all on the same scale and only differ by a factor of 2. It does alter the interpretations a little, but PC1 is still largely a measure of overall size.

crabs.pca2 <- prcomp(X, scale=FALSE) # Use the correlation matrix.
plot(crabs.pca2)

autoplot(crabs.pca2, data = crabs, colour='sex')

# not a big change

Repeat the analysis done in the notes.

PC1 is remarkably similar to the 2019-20 season. It contrasts goals against and losses vs goals for and wins (ie it measures if the team did well or not). PC2 is mainly measures the number of draws a team had. So Newcastle had lots of draws, and thus had a very small PC2 score. Manchester city won the legue so have the smallest PC1 score. Southampton finished bottom and have the largest PC1 score.

Q4

The decathlon2 data from the factoextra package contains data on 27 different decathletes’ performances during two different competitions. Let’s start by extracting their performance in the 10 different decathlon events at the Olympics.

library("factoextra")
data(decathlon2)
X <- decathlon2|> dplyr::filter(Competition=='OlympicG') |> dplyr::select(-Rank, -Points,-Competition)

Conduct PCA on these data, thinking about whether it is appropriate to use the correlation or covariance matrix. Give a scree plot, and determine how much information in the data is retained by the first two PCs. Interpret the leading PCs.

Plot the first two scores for the different athlete performances, labelling each point. From these plots, comment on particular strengths/weaknesses in some performances.

Solution

Firstly, we must decide whether to use the correlation or covariance matrix. As these events are measured on very different scales it makes sense to use the correlation matrix.

X.pca <- prcomp(X, scale=TRUE)
plot(X.pca)

fviz_eig(X.pca, addlabels = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 50))

The first 2 PCs explain 63% of the variance.

cumsum(X.pca$sdev^2/sum(X.pca$sdev^2))
 [1] 0.3854650 0.6272574 0.7783056 0.8728147 0.9280123 0.9598797 0.9809328
 [8] 0.9923592 0.9983383 1.0000000

A circle plot can help with the interpretations:

fviz_pca_var(X.pca)

The first PC is an overall measure of performance. Recall that for throws and jumps, large values are good, whereas for track events, smaller values are good. So large values of PC1 would indicate good overall performance (short sprint times, long throws). PC1 is most strongly related to discus, 100m, shot put, and the high and long jump. Note that it is negatively correlated with pole vault and positively correlated with 1500m, which is opposite to what we’d expect if it was just measuring performance (albeit these correlations are small).

We can see that the sprint events are highly correlated with each other (100m, 400m , 110m hurdles), as are discuss, shot put and high jump.

The second PC contrasts performance in pole vault and long jump, against the other events. A high value of PC2 might indicate a good pole vault or long jump, and/or poor 1500m.

To illustrate the individual athlete performances, we can use the following plot:

fviz_pca_ind(X.pca, 
             repel = TRUE # Avoid text overlapping (slow if many points)
             )

So we can see that the strong performances by Sebrle (1st), Clay (2nd), Karpov (3rd) and poor performance by Drews (last) etc.

Note that interpretation of PCA is not an exact science.
